						<div class="postbody">I know <a href="https://www.arduino.cc/en/Reference/SPI" class="postlink">Arduino can act as SPI master</a>, but can it act as a slave as well? If so, you might be able to have the thing snoop button reads in the background with D0 as data input, clock as clock input, and strobe as select or interrupt or whatever. Though D0 is analogous to the slave's output (MISO), your snooping device will need to treat it as the slave's input (MOSI). Then you won't need such a high frequency crystal because the NES doesn't clock the controllers faster than about 200 kHz (except during DMC glitches).<br /><br />An unrolled loop uses 9 cycles per bit, or 199 kHz:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda #1<br />sta $4016&nbsp; ; set strobe bit to 1<br />lsr a<br />sta $4016&nbsp; ; clear strobe bit to 0<br />.repeat 8<br />&nbsp; lda $4016<br />&nbsp; lsr a<br />&nbsp; rol cur_keys<br />.endrepeat<br /></div><br />Practical read loops are likely to be slower if they compensate for Famicom expansion controllers or use a loop. This loop takes 14 cycles per bit, or 128 kHz:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda #1<br />sta cur_keys&nbsp; ; place a 1 bit that doubles as a ring counter<br />sta $4016<br />lsr a<br />sta $4016<br />loop:<br />&nbsp; lda $4016<br />&nbsp; and #$03&nbsp; ; strip off all bits except input and FC expansion input<br />&nbsp; cmp #$01&nbsp; ; C=1 if either bit was set<br />&nbsp; rol cur_keys<br />&nbsp; bcc loop&nbsp; ; once the 1 bit gets shifted out to carry, we're done<br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

